PETER (over TV):
I'm an American
born and raised in Chicago.

33:37.780 --> 33:39.668
I have deep roots

33:39.710 --> 33:43.214
in this city,
in this country, and

33:43.250 --> 33:47.789
I am here because I feel
Chicago is in need of...

33:47.820 --> 33:49.685
ALICIA:
I'm wondering
ifI should call him back--

33:49.720 --> 33:51.529
the clerk
at the Seventh Circuit.

33:51.560 --> 33:53.050
We've only got an hour.

33:53.090 --> 33:54.193
No, not yet.

33:54.230 --> 33:55.652
We may have bought ourselves
some time

33:55.700 --> 33:58.521
with this appeal
on the anesthetic.

33:58.570 --> 34:00.219
How are you doing?

34:01.870 --> 34:04.065
I hate this.

34:05.840 --> 34:07.808
Being powerless.

34:07.840 --> 34:10.104
Yeah.

34:10.140 --> 34:12.779
He saw his daughter today.

34:12.810 --> 34:13.777
Carter did.

34:13.810 --> 34:15.516
That's something.

34:15.550 --> 34:18.519
That is more
than something.

34:22.590 --> 34:24.558
Will?

34:24.590 --> 34:26.729
Yeah.

34:27.790 --> 34:31.590
Could... we talk sometime?

34:32.670 --> 34:34.638
We can talk anytime.

34:34.670 --> 34:36.092
No, I mean...

34:36.740 --> 34:38.731
We need a moment.

34:40.410 --> 34:44.779
Just a moment when things don't
seem so all over the place.

34:44.810 --> 34:47.472
Okay, that's probably not now.

34:47.510 --> 34:48.738
(chuckles)
No.

34:48.780 --> 34:50.247
(knocking)

34:50.280 --> 34:52.248
Hi, Mrs. Florrick.

34:52.290 --> 34:54.884
Sorry, Zach said
I could use the bathroom.

34:54.920 --> 34:56.478
Sure.

34:56.520 --> 34:58.659
I'm Zach's _
study partner Nisa.

34:58.690 --> 35:00.157
Hi, Nisa.

35:00.190 --> 35:02.226
WOMAN (over P.A.):
At this time I'd like to ask

35:02.260 --> 35:05.297
all passengers
on flight 1893 to Orlando

35:05.330 --> 35:08.697
to please approach the gate
for final boarding.

35:10.600 --> 35:12.568
Dr. Grossman?

35:12.610 --> 35:15.306
Um, do you have
a minute, please?

35:15.340 --> 35:16.568
Do I know you?

35:16.610 --> 35:18.601
I'm working for the
Carter Wright defense team.

35:18.650 --> 35:21.107
I really need a minute
of your time, please.

35:31.960 --> 35:34.190
WOMAN (over PA):
This is the final boarding call
for flight 1893

35:34.230 --> 35:35.424
to Orlando.

35:35.460 --> 35:36.893
KALINDA: But the science
has changed, sir,

35:36.930 --> 35:39.490
the arson science
has changed.

35:39.530 --> 35:41.293
Yes, but the physics hasn't.

35:41.340 --> 35:43.490
You see these "V"
patterns on the wall?

35:43.540 --> 35:45.929
A fire typically
burns up and out,

35:45.970 --> 35:47.767
and a "V" pattern indicates
a point of origin

35:47.810 --> 35:50.779
for a fire produced by
accelerants, ergo arson.

35:50.810 --> 35:52.698
Yes, but this can also
indicate the presence

35:52.750 --> 35:55.344
of a knob and tube wiring
burn-off.

35:56.380 --> 35:57.813
Are you in the trade, miss?

35:57.850 --> 35:59.886
No, but I just
read a paper

35:59.920 --> 36:01.956
by a young clerk
in the Seventh Circuit

36:01.990 --> 36:04.458
aboutchanges
in arson science,

36:04.490 --> 36:05.923
especially when applied
to structures

36:05.960 --> 36:07.825
over 80 years old,
as this apartment was.

36:07.860 --> 36:10.693
Well, certainly "V" patterns
aren't always indicative

36:10.730 --> 36:12.595
of a point of origin, but...

36:12.630 --> 36:14.962
You see these brown stains?

36:15.000 --> 36:17.537
They indicate accelerant
in the hallway.

36:17.570 --> 36:19.367
And I really must
get on my plane.

36:19.410 --> 36:20.365
No, sir.

36:20.410 --> 36:21.434
Look, these brown stains

36:21.480 --> 36:24.574
are just as likely to come
from flashover burns.

36:24.610 --> 36:26.305
You know about the
changes In arson SCIence.

36:26.350 --> 36:27.749
You know_ what I'm
saying Is true.

36:27.780 --> 36:29.873
No, I know what you're saying
is possible, that's all.

36:29.920 --> 36:32.616
Yeah, and all Carter Wright
needs is what's possible.

36:32.650 --> 36:34.959
Look, you said at the trial
that you were 100% positive

36:34.990 --> 36:36.855
that these stains were
proof of an accelerant.

36:36.890 --> 36:40.724
Now, if your opinion
has changed...

36:40.760 --> 36:42.955
There are other
people you can ask.

36:43.000 --> 36:44.888
No, sir.

36:44.930 --> 36:47.967
There are other
experts you can get.

36:48.000 --> 36:50.230
Not in an hour
and not with your authority.

36:50.270 --> 36:51.567
I'm sorry.

36:51.610 --> 36:53.703
Actually, I'm sorry.

36:55.610 --> 36:57.578
I can't help you.

36:57.610 --> 36:59.942
You can help me.

36:59.980 --> 37:02.847
You are responsible for Carter
Wright being on death row.

37:02.880 --> 37:05.986
It's your responsibility
to correct that mistake.

37:06.020 --> 37:07.089
You're not getting
on a plane.

37:07.120 --> 37:11.329
You're going to write an
affidavit to that effect now.

37:11.360 --> 37:12.884
You just need
a moment to realize

37:12.930 --> 37:14.989
that this is
the right thing to do.

37:15.030 --> 37:17.794
Why don't I give you
that moment?

37:26.010 --> 37:27.602
MODERATOR (on TV):
Thank you, Mr. Florrick.

37:27.640 --> 37:29.699
Good, I got that part.
What time do we have?

37:29.740 --> 37:30.934
We've got 20 minutes.

37:30.980 --> 37:32.504
Kalinda is rushing
the affidavit.

37:32.550 --> 37:33.539
We've got the addendum here.

37:33.580 --> 37:35.013
You just take care
of the preamble.

37:35.050 --> 37:36.017
Got it.

37:36.050 --> 37:37.517
I will phone him in a minute.

37:37.550 --> 37:38.710
Tell him it's on its way.
Are you phoning Diane?

37:38.750 --> 37:42.049
Yes, I'm... Let me call you
right back. You taking off?

37:42.090 --> 37:44.422
Yeah, unless you got some
floors that need sweeping.

37:45.930 --> 37:47.352
GRACE:
Mom, come in here.

37:47.390 --> 37:48.698
They're talking
about you.

37:48.730 --> 37:50.357
Mr. Florrick, the question
isn't about the past;

37:50.400 --> 37:52.595
(volume increasing):
it's about the future.

37:52.630 --> 37:54.530
Well, I'm here to
talk about policy.

37:54.570 --> 37:56.435
I'm here to talk about
the future of Chicago,

37:56.470 --> 37:58.700
so if you have any
questions about policy,

37:58.740 --> 38:00.628
I-I'd be happy
to answer them.

38:00.670 --> 38:01.773
But isn't_that
hypocritical?

38:01.810 --> 38:03.675
I mean, you sell yourself as
a happily married candidate.

38:03.710 --> 38:05.473
So I ask you again, sir:

38:05.510 --> 38:08.377
has your wife forgiven
you for your infidelity?

38:08.420 --> 38:09.648
Mom, are you coming?

38:10.650 --> 38:12.641
MODERATOR:
Mr. Florrick?

38:14.120 --> 38:15.348
Sir?

38:15.390 --> 38:16.789
My marriage is none of your...

38:16.820 --> 38:18.048
Mom !_
...your busmess.

38:24.930 --> 38:28.093
Sir, are you aware of
what you just said?

38:28.130 --> 38:30.030
Yes, I am.

38:30.070 --> 38:32.038
Do you have any
more questions?

38:34.070 --> 38:36.038
Yep, it's me.

38:36.080 --> 38:38.640
My dad swore on TV.

38:38.680 --> 38:39.806
Oh.

38:39.850 --> 38:41.044
Nothing?

38:41.080 --> 38:42.172
Nope.

38:42.220 --> 38:45.644
Will said he'd phone when
they tell us the decision.

38:45.690 --> 38:48.045
Look, you get back
to your life.

38:48.090 --> 38:49.489
I'll wait.

38:49.520 --> 38:51.579
No, this is my life.

38:51.630 --> 38:52.585
(phone rings)

38:52.630 --> 38:53.949
That's Will.

38:53.990 --> 38:55.025
Hello.

38:55.060 --> 38:56.652
JASON:
Mrs. Florrick?

38:56.700 --> 38:58.053
Yes.

38:58.100 --> 38:59.499
This is Jason Kerrigan

38:59.530 --> 39:01.395
with the Seventh
Circuit Court of Appeals.

39:01.440 --> 39:03.396
I have Judge Jerry Glendon
with a question for you.

39:03.440 --> 39:04.407
Do you have a minute?

39:04.440 --> 39:05.737
Uh, yes, I do.

39:05.770 --> 39:06.737
Please hold.

39:06.770 --> 39:08.408
(whispering):
Get Will.
Why?

39:08.440 --> 39:09.429
It's Judge Glendon.

39:11.880 --> 39:13.404
(phone rings)
Yeah, it's Will.

39:13.450 --> 39:15.145
KALINDA:
Judge Glendon
just phoned Alicia.

39:15.180 --> 39:17.068
He what?

39:17.120 --> 39:18.041
Yeah, just now.

39:18.080 --> 39:20.082
She's on the phone
waiting for a question.

39:20.120 --> 39:21.485
This is Judge Glendon.

39:21.520 --> 39:22.612
Who am I speaking to?

39:22.660 --> 39:24.059
Alicia Florrick,
Your Honor.

39:24.090 --> 39:25.057
Thank you for taking my call.

39:25.090 --> 39:26.057
You have a second?

39:26.090 --> 39:27.978
Yes, um, of course I do.

39:28.030 --> 39:31.761
It's just, um,
I'm a second-year associate.

39:31.800 --> 39:33.995
I just delivered
the addendum-- actually,

39:34.030 --> 39:35.668
not even the addendum--
I delivered the first a...

39:35.700 --> 39:37.167
Shut up,
shut up. You.

39:37.200 --> 39:39.430
I'm sorry, this is
the number I was given.

39:39.470 --> 39:41.506
Jason, am I supposed
to be talking to somebody else?

39:41.540 --> 39:43.770
Actually, I'm sorry,
Your Honor.

39:43.810 --> 39:46.108
I can answer
your questions.

39:46.150 --> 39:47.606
WILL:
Kalinda, what's going on?

39:47.650 --> 39:49.641
Shh, she's still on
the phone with him.

39:49.680 --> 39:51.079
GLENDON:
I'm reading the new affidavit

39:51.120 --> 39:53.543
from this arson expert
Dr. Grossman,

39:53.590 --> 39:55.808
and he seems to have left
a window to this being...

39:55.860 --> 39:57.111
let's see...

39:57.160 --> 40:00.049
An accidental fire,
yes, Your Honor.

40:00.090 --> 40:02.627
He's asking if it was
an accidental fire.

40:02.660 --> 40:04.093
Tell her to push for innocence.

40:04.130 --> 40:05.495
And you talked to him today?

40:05.530 --> 40:06.565
Dr. Grossman?

40:06.600 --> 40:08.636
One of my associates did...

40:08.670 --> 40:09.466
(mouthing)
...and

40:09.500 --> 40:12.560
I talked to him,
of course, after that.

40:12.610 --> 40:14.134
So my question is this.

40:14.170 --> 40:17.731
Well, actually, you know what
I'm going to ask you, don't you?

40:22.250 --> 40:25.583
Yes, I do, Your Honor.

40:25.620 --> 40:27.918
He's innocent.

40:27.950 --> 40:29.952
Carter is innocent.

40:31.860 --> 40:33.521
Look, I can order a new trial;

40:33.560 --> 40:34.356
I can deal with the heat.

40:34.390 --> 40:36.051
But why should I trust
this doctor

40:36.100 --> 40:37.988
if he so easily changed
his mind?

40:38.030 --> 40:40.590
Because he didn't
so easily change his mind.

40:40.630 --> 40:42.734
He changed his
mind in the face

40:42.770 --> 40:44.761
Of a man's innocence.

40:46.810 --> 40:50.678
So much _of what we do is
uncertain, Your Honor.

40:50.710 --> 40:55.079
So much of my day is working
between right and wrong.

40:56.750 --> 40:58.718
But this has to be right.

40:58.750 --> 41:01.753
To do this to a man...

41:01.790 --> 41:04.111
it has to be right.

41:06.260 --> 41:08.626
Thank you, ma'am.

41:08.660 --> 41:09.695
Good night.

41:09.730 --> 41:11.721
(hangs up)

41:14.300 --> 41:16.860
You did good.

41:18.970 --> 41:21.939
You did.

41:21.980 --> 41:23.129
Trust me.

41:33.850 --> 41:36.489
Got the paperwork
from the court.

41:51.940 --> 41:53.931
Dad.

42:09.590 --> 42:11.182
REPORTER:
And just hours
before his scheduled execution,

42:11.220 --> 42:12.323
Seventh Circuit Judge

42:12.360 --> 42:16.228
Jerry Glendon called for a stay
of execution of Wright.

42:16.260 --> 42:18.319
It is expected
that his case will be retried.

42:18.360 --> 42:20.328
Ten years ago,
Wright was convicted

42:20.370 --> 42:22.736
of the first-degree murder
of his wife Carolyn.

42:22.770 --> 42:24.761
Since that time,
Wright's execution

42:24.810 --> 42:26.209
has resisted numerous appeals.

42:26.240 --> 42:27.264
(turns off TV)

42:31.240 --> 42:33.208
ZACH:
You see Dad?

42:33.250 --> 42:35.218
I did.

42:35.250 --> 42:37.070
He swore on TV.

